<!--
  bc-k8s-audit.xml — Custom Wazuh rules for Kubernetes audit log telemetry.

  Rule ID range: 100400-100499 (reserved for bc-k8s)
  Telemetry source: K8s API server audit logs.

  !!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!
  WARNING — RULES IN THIS FILE DO NOT FIRE TODAY. DO NOT BUILD SOAR
  PLAYBOOKS THAT DEPEND ON THESE RULE IDs UNTIL INGESTION IS WIRED.
  !!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!

  Blocking gap 1 — EKS audit log ingestion not enabled:
    EKS does not emit audit logs to CloudWatch by default. Enabling requires:
      cluster_enabled_log_types = ["audit", "authenticator"]
    in the EKS module (eks.tf), plus either:
      (a) a Wazuh CloudWatch Logs wodle pointed at the
          /aws/eks/bc-uatms-prd-eks/cluster log group, OR
      (b) a Lambda subscriber that ships log events to the manager socket.
    Neither is currently deployed. Until done, zero K8s audit events reach
    the manager and all rules in this file are dead letters.

  Blocking gap 2 — Wazuh cannot match inside JSON arrays:
    The Wazuh rule engine evaluates <field> matches against a flat JSON
    document extracted by a decoder. The requestObject.spec.containers field
    in a K8s audit event is a JSON array of container objects. Wazuh's
    decoder will not explode array elements into individually matchable
    fields, so a rule like:
      <field name="requestObject.spec.containers.securityContext.privileged">true</field>
    will NEVER match — containers[0].securityContext.privileged is buried
    inside an array element, not at the top-level key path the field match
    expects. To make this work reliably, a pre-processing step is needed:
    either a custom Wazuh decoder that extracts the first/any privileged
    container flag, or a Lambda/Logstash enrichment that flattens the array
    before forwarding to Wazuh.
    Current rule 100400 is therefore a design placeholder only.

  Deployed to: /var/ossec/etc/rules/bc-k8s-audit.xml on the manager
               by phase3-install-wazuh.sh via S3 sync on instance boot.
-->
<group name="bc-k8s,kubernetes,audit,">

  <!-- ============================================================
       100400 — Privileged pod created
       MITRE: T1611 (Escape to Host)
       Level 14: critical — privileged pods can mount the host kernel.
       Expected false positives: Suricata DaemonSet (needs NET_ADMIN),
       wazuh-agent DaemonSet. Suppress by namespace if needed.
  ============================================================ -->
  <rule id="100400" level="14">
    <decoded_as>json</decoded_as>
    <field name="verb">create</field>
    <field name="objectRef.resource">pods</field>
    <field name="requestObject.spec.containers.securityContext.privileged">true</field>
    <description>K8s privileged pod created in $(objectRef.namespace) by $(user.username)</description>
    <mitre>
      <id>T1611</id>
    </mitre>
    <group>container_escape,privilege_escalation,</group>
  </rule>

</group>
